body: "## Story\nAs an organization running real business workflows on pm (the pm-8ngt vision: companies and their business logic built on pm SDK primitives), I can define principals (roles/teams/agents) and item-level policies — who may create, transition, close, or approve which item types and statuses — and have pm enforce them consistently at the SDK layer, so that the CLI, MCP, and every custom tool built on the SDK apply the same rules.\n\n## Why this is a distinct gap\n- pm-f4r1 (shipped) gives per-type allowed status *transitions* — a state machine, but principal-blind: any author may perform any allowed transition.\n- Extension sandbox permissions (pm-pl53 lineage) govern what *extensions* may do, not what *authors/agents* may do to items.\n- Governance validation (pm-33cw) checks data quality after the fact; there is no policy gate at mutation time.\n\n## Honest constraint (must anchor the ADR)\nGit-native storage means anyone with repo write access can bypass the tool entirely. Enforcement is therefore layered, not absolute: (1) advisory/enforcing gate in the SDK mutation path (same knob pattern as governance policy_modes), (2) verification in pm validate + CI so bypasses are detected post-hoc, (3) the real trust boundary stays git (branch protection, required checks). The ADR must state this explicitly rather than promising DB-style ACLs.\n\n## Scope (spike + ADR only, parked)\n- Survey: schema/workflows.json extension point for principal rules; author identity model (PM_AUTHOR is self-declared today — policy needs an identity/trust stance); approval-step modeling (Decision items? status gates?).\n- Produce an ADR (accept/reject) under pm-m2u1; implementation items only after acceptance.\n- Parked at P4 until the v1.0 GA stability contract (pm-agou) fixes the grammar/SDK surface this would extend.\n\n## Duplicate check (2026-07-07 review #16)\nSearched \"access control permissions roles\", \"approval workflow role policy\" — matches were extension sandbox permissions and pm-f4r1 transition workflows only; no item covers principal-based item-level policy."
